SIMPLE: goad
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Goad
<hw>Goad</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>g⟦amac⟧d</ets>;
perh. akin to AS. <ets>g⟦amac⟧r</ets> a dart, and E. <ets>gore</ets>.
See <er>Gore</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>A pointed instrument
used to urge on a beast; hence, any necessity that urges or
stimulates.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The daily <qex>goad</qex> urging him to the daily toil.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Goad</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Goad
<hw>Goad</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Goaded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Goading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To prick; to drive with a goad;
hence, to urge forward, or to rouse by anything pungent, severe,
irritating, or inflaming; to stimulate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That temptation that doth <qex>goad</qex> us on.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To urge; stimulate; excite; arouse; irritate;
incite; instigate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>goaded</ent>⟦br⟧
